<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-561-079  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 561 079.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Data Communications  Oct 1990 v19 n13 p37(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>LEC circuits offer big savings to anyone who looks. (localexchange carrier) (WAN Views) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Van Norman, Harrell J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Network managers can save substantial amounts of money on localexchange carrier (LEC) bills by not simply accepting the carrier'sdesignation of a leased-line service or routing strategy.andO;Selecting hubless leased line service over conventional digitaldata service (DDS) can yield savings of as much as 60 percent,while choosing LEC bridging over long-distance carrier bridgingcan yield savings of up to 40 percent for circuits with three ormore drops in a single Local Access and Transport Area (LATA).andO;Carriers usually choose the most direct routing path for localcircuits, but since the shortest route is not always the cheapest,substantial savings are possible through customer-specifiedrouting.andP;  LECs do not present these new services to customers as ageneral rule, so it is good practice for network managers toselect network design packages that offer extensive local tariffinformation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Cost of CommunicationsCommunications Service SuppliersTutorialTelecommunications ServicesNetwork ManagementCost Reduction.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Hubless digital service and DDS. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>